<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910114-0164</DOCNO><DOCID>910114-0164.</DOCID><HL>   U.S. Warns Public   Of Terrorism Threat   If Mideast War Erupts</HL><DATE>01/14/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14</SO><CO>   MDEST FREST AFRIC</CO><GV>STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The State Department warned the public thatanti-American terrorism likely will rise sharply around theworld if war breaks out in the Persian Gulf, and it advisedAmericans to take a variety of precautions.   &quot;The American public should be aware that in the event ofmilitary action involving the United States in the PersianGulf, the threat of terrorism against American citizens wouldincrease significantly,&quot; spokesman Richard Boucher said.</LP><TEXT>   In addition, the department issued an advisory cautioningthat, with or without a war, increased anti-American violenceis likely in the Middle East, South Asia and North Africabecause of the crisis.   It advised Americans to defer nonessential travel to thesebroad areas, and especially to Iraq, Kuwait, Jordan, Israel,Mauritania, Sudan, Yemen, Algeria, Morocco, Pakistan,Tunisia, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Qatar, and the United ArabEmirates.   Americans already in these countries should considerleaving, the department said.   Mr. Boucher said the department is advising that allAmericans traveling anywhere abroad &quot;stay in close touch withthe nearest U.S. embassy or consulate. They should be alertand pay attention to anyone who may be observing them. Ifthey become concerned about something unusual, they shouldcontact the local police.&quot;   He added: &quot;Americans overseas should exercise caution whenin or near U.S. military or civilian facilities. Shouldhostilities begin, Americans should keep informed throughradio and television broadcasts.&quot;   The spokesman insisted that these warnings aren't based onany credible evidence of any specific threat. Rather, hesaid, they stem from previously disclosed evidence thatterrorists have been seen sizing up possible American targetsoverseas.   &quot;While it is likely that terrorist events may occur forwhich we have no full warning,&quot; he said, &quot;should specific andcredible information on a threat to the American public bereceived, the Department of State will provide informationfor travelers and for other concerned parties.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>